\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baryon acoustic oscillations are a signature of the early universe imprinted
 in the distribution of galaxies and dark matters at the present epoch.
 As the early universe expands and its temperature drops, sound waves propagatin
g in the baryon-photon plasma freeze into the matter distribution at decoupling.
 This leaves a characteristic peak in two-point correlation functions where
 the position of the peak is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim150{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The BAO method utilizes this characteristic scale of the sound horizon
 as a standard ruler (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "1997PhRvL..79.3806T,1998ApJ...495...29G,1999MNRAS.304...75E"

\end_inset

), which is insensitive to astrophysical processes on small scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the primordeal density fluctuation is linear and well understood,
 dark matter (DM) density field at low redshifts suffers from non-linear
 growth of structure, which makes the BAO peak broadened and shifted.
 Furthermore, what we can actually observe is distribution of galaxies,
 which are biased tracers of DM particles.
 The galaxy bias and the effect of redshift-space distortions (due to peculiar
 motion of galaxies) cause the systematic bias on the measurement of the
 BAO peak.
 
\color black
In order to reduce the errors, Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eisenstein2007"

\end_inset

 proposed a method termed “reconstruction” to sharpen the BAO feature by
 reducing the non-linearities.
 The assumption behind the reconstruction method is that the major source
 of degradation of the BAO peak comes from the bulk flows, which can be
 modeled by Zel'dovich displacement in Lagrangian perturbation theory (LPT).
 By shifting back the positions of galaxies by the estimated Zel'dovich
 displacement, the BAO peak is sharpened as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bao_recon1"

\end_inset

.
 This is because the reconstruction method supress the damping tem appeared
 in non-linear evolution of density fluctuations and restore the high-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes in the power spectrum.
 There has been many studies both numerically and analytically [cite:xxx]
 to verify the technique, and it has been widely used to observational studies
 
\color inherit
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "2007ApJ...664..660E,2009PhRvD..79f3523P,2009PhRvD..80l3501N"

\end_inset

)
\color black
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../Dropbox/Tomomi/Prospectus/bao_recon1.png
	lyxscale 40
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bao_recon1"

\end_inset

The one-dimensional correlation functions for DM with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model at z=0.0 before (solid) and after reconstruction with smoothing scales
 of 5
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (dotted) and 10
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (short dashed).
 The long-dashed line shows the peak in the initial conditions.
 The figure is from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "2009PhRvD..80l3501N"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we investigate how galaxy bias affects on the shift of the
 BAO peak before and after reconstruction.
 Because the shiftin the BAO peak will cause the systematic bias for the
 infered cosmological parameters, it is crucal to understand how much shift
 is caused by galaxy bias.
 A similar study is done by Ref.xxx at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, but we are now testing the effect of galaxy bias at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

 where the non-linear effects are more significant in galaxy samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[structure of the paper]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations/Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HACC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the HACC simulation [cite:xxx] in this work; HACC uses a hybrid parallel
 algorithmic structure, splitting the force calculation into a specially
 designed grid-based long/medium range spectral particle mesh (PM) component
 and a short-range solver, which uses direct particle-particle interactions,
 i.e., a P
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

M algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1988csup.book.....H"

\end_inset

.
 The simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $300$
\end_inset

 long time steps and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 subcycles.
 The simulation assumes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.2648$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.7352$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}h^{2}=0.02258$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}=0.963$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.71$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $4096^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc}$
\end_inset

 box giving a particle mass of about 
\begin_inset Formula $5.3\times10^{10}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos are identified using the friends-of-friends (FOF) algorithm
 with the linking length of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.168$
\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 We have four outputs of the simulation and subdivide each of our 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times(4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 volumes into 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times64=256$
\end_inset

 subvolumes to estimate the covariance matrix for galaxy correlation functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[check force resolution and the meaning of the number of time steps]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Occupation Distributions (HODs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Galaxies are biased tracer of DM particles, and it is important to understand
 how galaxy biases affect to the peak position of BAO.
 To test this, we need to generate galaxy mock catalogs with various galaxy
 biases.
 We use the Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD) method, w
\color inherit
hich specifies the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(N|M)$
\end_inset

 that a halo with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 hosts 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 galaxies.
 The underlying assumption of the HOD is that the number of galaxies which
 live in a halo correlates with its halo mass.
 The HOD functional form (based on a number of free parameters, 5 in our
 case) provides probabilities for the number of central and satellite galaxies
 based on the masses of halos that host those galaxies.
 A halo hosts a central galaxy with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

 and a number of satellite galaxies given by a Poisson distribution with
 mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle=\frac{1}{2}{\rm erfc}\left[\frac{{\rm ln}(M_{cut}/M)}{\sqrt{2}\sigma}\right],\label{eq:Ncen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle=N_{cen}(M)\left(\frac{M-\kappa M_{cut}}{M_{1}}\right)^{\alpha},\label{eq:Nsat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{cut}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are free parameters and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the halo mass.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{sat}(M)$
\end_inset

 is zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $M<\kappa M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 and halos do not host satellite galaxies without a central galaxy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2005ApJ...633..791Z"

\end_inset

.
 The total number of galaxies hosted by each halo is a sum of the number
 of central and satellite galaxies.
 Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ncen"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nsat"

\end_inset

 are not the only possible functional form for the HOD, and it is trivial
 to change this.
 However, these forms are known to successfully reproduce the clustering
 of the BOSS galaxies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...728..126W"

\end_inset

 and are therefore a convenient choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to construct samples of different galaxy biases, we construct realizati
ons of HOD models with the fixed parameters (
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{1}=14.0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1.013$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=1.0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0.85$
\end_inset

), except for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 which we vary from 12.5 to 14.1 in steps of 0.2.

\color red
 The reason we only vary the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}$
\end_inset

 is because this parameter determines the overall number of central galaxies
 which affect to the galaxy bias most effectively.

\color inherit
 The resulting nine HODs span a range of biases from 1.5 to 3.0 corresponding
 to the number densities from xxx to xxx.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After assigning a number of galaxies to each halo, we distribute those galaxies
 within the halo.
 The central galaxy is always at the center of the halo, while the distribution
 of satellite galaxies follows a spherically symmetric NFW profile specified
 by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(r)=\frac{4\rho_{s}}{\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}}(1+\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}})^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the density at the characteristic scale 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}=R_{{\rm vir}}/c$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the virial radius for the halo and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the concentration parameter.
 We use the emulator described in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013ApJ...768..123K"

\end_inset

 to generate a table of concentration-mass relations for halos at each redshift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set the velocity of the central galaxy to be equal to the host halo velocity.
 We assume that satellite galaxies are randomly moving inside the host halos.
 Therefore, the velocities of the satellite galaxies are the sum of their
 host halo velocity and a random virial component.
 For this random component, we draw from a Gaussian distribution with zero
 mean and variance given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle v_{x}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{y}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{z}^{2}\rangle=\frac{1}{3}\frac{GM}{R_{{\rm vir}}}.\label{eq:variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been several discussions about velocity bias and how to assign/define
 the velocity for galaxies (e.g., using only inner 10% of particles to define
 velocities for central galaxies) [citation:xxx]; however, we expect that
 the velocities only affect on scales smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $30h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 in configuration-space, which is smaller than the scales that we measure
 the BAO peak.
 Note that it is not clear how the velocities affect on long-wave modes
 in Fourier-space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-linear growth of structure broadens and shifts the BAO peak.
 The reconstruction method, originally proposed by Ref.xxx, partially removes
 the non-linear effect and recovers the linear density field.
 As a consequence, the reconstruction method sharpens and shifts back the
 BAO peak, and its mechanism is well explained in terms of LPT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In LPT, the Eulerian distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is described as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}=\vec{q}+\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

 is the initial position and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is the displacement vector field.
 The density field in configuration-space and Fourier-space are described
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(\vec{x})=(int)d^{3}q\delta^{(D)}(\vec{x}-\vec{q}-\vec{\Psi})-1\Leftrightarrow\delta(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}-1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution of the displacement field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 follows the Euler equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}\vec{\Psi}}{dt^{2}}+2H\frac{d\vec{\Psi}}{dt}=-\nabla_{x}\phi(\vec{x}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the gravitational potential.
 In the first-order LPT, the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

, which is often called as Zel'dovich displacement, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}=i\frac{\vec{k}}{k^{2}}\delta_{0}(\vec{k}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

 is the linear density field.
 What the reconstruction method does is estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 by assuming that most of contribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 comes from the Zel'dovich displacement and shifting back the position of
 the particles (called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

displacement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{d}(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{(\Psi}-\vec{\Psi}^{(1)})}-1),
\]

\end_inset

and compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

 using the random particles and moving their positions by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{s}(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}}-1).
\]

\end_inset

The reconstructed density field is obtained by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{recon}=\delta_{d}-\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 In the linear regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}\rightarrow\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

.The first term in the bracket goes to zero when the displacement field is
 the Zel'dovich displacement and the second term becomes the linear density
 field.
 In reality, we cannot measure the linear density field and have to use
 the non-linear density field to estimate the Zel'dovich displacement field.
 Because of this reason, we smooth out the non-linear density field to kill
 the high-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A basic algorithm is given below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smooth the real-space density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 to filter out high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes with a Gaussian smoothing of scale 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(k)={\rm e}^{-(kR)^{2}/2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the Zel'dovich displacement field from linear perturbation theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\color{black}\vec{s}}(\vec{k})\equiv i\frac{\vec{k}}{k^{2}}S(k)\delta_{r}(\vec{k}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shift the particles by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{s}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

 and recompute the displacement density field (denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generate randomly displaced particles and shift them by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field (denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the reconstructed density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}=\delta_{d}-\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the density field is in redshift-space, it requires one more additional
 step to recover the real-space density field from the redshift-space density
 field prior to applying the reconstruction method.
 The only difference is that there is an extra growth factor to estimate
 the linear velocity field and we only shift back the particle positions
 along the line-of-sight.
 The detailed steps of recovering the real-space density field is in ch.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitting Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We construct models of correlation functions with fiducial cosmology to
 measure the position of the BAO peak.
 For the case of isotropic BAO measurements, we only use the monopole term
 of the correlation functions and use the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to measure the shift of the peak, while we model both monopole and quadrupole
 terms of the correlation functions for the case of anisotropic measurements
 using the warping parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Isotropic 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:fit_isotropic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure the BAO scale using the methodology in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013arXiv1303.4666A"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically, we describe the observed correlation function by 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm fit}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{{\rm fit}}(r)=B\xi_{t}(\alpha r)+A_{0}+A_{1}/r+A_{2}/r^{2},\label{eq:model1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a template correlation function, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the galaxy bias squared and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0,1,2}$
\end_inset

 represent nuisance parameters to account for shot noise, nonlinear evolution
 of the matter density field and the mapping from matter to galaxies.
 We give a Gaussian prior on bias parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that we measure linear galaxy bias 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 between the template correlation function and data on 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[40h^{-1}{\rm Mpc},50h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}]$
\end_inset

 and give a prior to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}\sim1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $B=b^{2}B_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measures the shift in the BAO scale relative to what is assumed for the
 template function, and is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha\equiv\left(\frac{D_{{\rm V}}(z)}{r_{{\rm d}}}\right)\left(\frac{r_{{\rm d,fid}}}{D_{{\rm V}}^{{\rm fid}}(z)}\right),\label{eq:alpha_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm d}}$
\end_inset

 is the sound horizon at the drag epoch and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{{\rm V}}\equiv\left[cz(1+z)^{2}D_{{\rm A}}(z)^{2}H^{-1}(z)\right]^{1/3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{{\rm A}}$
\end_inset

 being the angular diameter distance and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(z)$
\end_inset

, the Hubble parameter.
 In the absence of systematics, we expect 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

; deviations from this represent a systematic bias to the inferred distance-reds
hift relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The template correlation function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}(r)$
\end_inset

 is given by a Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}(k)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{t}(r)=(P_{{\rm lin}}(k)-P_{nw}(k))e^{-\frac{k^{2}\Sigma^{2}}{2}}+P_{nw}(k),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{{\rm lin}}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the linear power spectrum and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{nw}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the no-wiggle power spectrum described in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1998ApJ...496..605E"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear parameter that accounts for the broadening of the BAO peak
 due to nonlinear evolution.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=7.5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for pre-reconstruction and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=2.5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for post-reconstruction, and we will discuss the reason for those choices
 in the next section.
 We determine the parameters by minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}=(\xi_{{\rm HOD}}-\xi_{{\rm fit}})^{{\rm T}}C^{-1}(\xi_{{\rm HOD}}-\xi_{{\rm fit}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse covariance matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm HOD}}$
\end_inset

 is a correlation function which 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm fit}}$
\end_inset

 is fitted to.
 We consider the measured correlation function from 
\begin_inset Formula $60h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $160h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 in bins of 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for a total of 25 data points.
 Since all parameters except 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are linear, we perform the minimization on a grid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values, computing the minimum value of the other parameters directly.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measures the shift of the BAO peak from its original position predicted
 by linear perturbation theory.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 implies that there is no shift of the BAO peak.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effects of Smoothing Scales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we discuss how the smoothing parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 in the template correlation function affects to the measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is xxx, which is computed from xxx.
 We use the sample with 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

.
 For each sample, we change the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sigma_prerecon"

\end_inset

 shows the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a function of various values for the smoothing parameter in real-space
 before reconstruction and the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values.
 While decreasing the smoothing scale makes the shift of the BAO peak smaller
 monotonically, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=7.5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 gives the smallest value and therefore the best fit.
 We repeat the same thing for the case of post-reconstruction, as shown
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sigma_post"

\end_inset

.
 After reconstruction, the smoothing scale which gives the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 value is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=2.5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, which is much smaller than what we expected.
 [explain what we expected and why it's a reasonable thing to expect] While
 the smoothing scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 really changes the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value for the case of pre-reconstruction, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value does not show significant changes for the case of post-reconstruction.
 [possible reasons?]
\end_layout

