\begin_layout Section
Results for Isotropic BAO: Real-Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we show the results of the isotropic BAO analysis with
 and without reconstruction (i.e., measuring the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values from the real-space correlation functions) discussed in Sec.
 xxx.
 Here, we use the samples generated from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method in order to remove the variance on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values due to subsampling halos, which is particularly large for the samples
 with high biases.
 We discuss the effect of subsampling and compare the results between the
 regular HOD and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD methods in Sec.
 xxx.
 We show the results of the effect of galaxy bias on the BAO measurements
 without reconstruction in Sec.xxx and with reconstruction in Sec.xxx.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Weighted HOD
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:weightHOD"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*ask about eq.
 7 in Noh et al...
 how 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to the smoothing scales...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we were measuring the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for each sample, we realized that the size of effects on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measurements due to the choice of random seeds is not negligible and the
 exact values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are very sensitive to the choice of the random seeds; for the case of the
 samples with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=14.1$
\end_inset

, the effect is larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $1\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 This is because large values for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm cut}}$
\end_inset

 implies more variations in subsampling halos to host galaxies.
 One way to remove the variation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 due to subsampling is generating enough number of realizations; however,
 we can also avoid this problem by giving halos weights which are the expected
 number of galaxies, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

.
 We call this method the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD to differentiate with the regular HOD method.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

 shows the expected number of central and satellite galaxies as a function
 of halo mass.
 While the expected numbers of central and satellite galaxy are treated
 as probabilities in the regular HOD method, the sum of the expected number
 of central and satellite galaxies is treated as weights in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD.
 In this way, the measurement of the BAO peak will not suffer from the variation
s due to subsampling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[mention about the shot noise for the weighted case]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we can use this method in real-space but not in redshift-space,
 because we cannot model the FOG effect properly with weights.
 So, for the case of anisotropic BAO analysis, we need to generate enough
 number of samples, which converged to the result from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variation_hod"

\end_inset

 shows the comparison between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values measured from the regular HOD and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD samples.
 For the case of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method, we first compute the correlation functions with the given weights
 and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values for the 64 samples denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{weight}$
\end_inset

.
 For the regular HOD samples, we generate three different realizations (in
 total of 192 samples) for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 and five (or six?) realizations (in total of 320 samples) for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=14.1$
\end_inset

, and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we compare the differences in the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values between 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{weight}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}$
\end_inset

.
 For both cases, the mean of the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $<\alpha_{HOD}-\alpha_{weight}>$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm0.02\%$
\end_inset

; the error of the mean for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.45\%$
\end_inset

, while it is 
\begin_inset Formula $2.44\%$
\end_inset

 for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=14.1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*implication/interpretation?
\end_layout

