\begin_layout Standard
In order to understand the correlation in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values between different galaxy samples, we compare the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values measured from the samples with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.9$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $14.1$
\end_inset

 (corresponding to the galaxy bias of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.8$
\end_inset

 and denoted as HOD3 and HOD9 respectively) to the samples with the lowest
 galaxy bias (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 denoted as HOD1).
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter_prerecon"

\end_inset

, we plot every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value measured from each sample.
 From the figure, we see that there is a correlation between the shifts
 measured for the HOD1 and HOD3 samples and its cross-correlation coefficient
 is xxx.
 On the other hand, there is little correlation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values between HOD1 and HOD9 where the cross-correlation coefficient is
 xxx).
 There are two possible sources for this uncorrelation; one is due to the
 large shot noise for the sample of HOD9, and the other is due to reconstruction
 that the number density of galaxies for HOD9 is small and it can cause
 an incomplete estimation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

