\begin_layout Standard
There are three possible sources for the biases and the scatter in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measurements : the initial conditions (no biases, but scatter), the matter
 and the actual galaxy population.
 For any samples we consider, the first two are common; however, the last
 one (i.e., galaxy bias) is not.
 Knowing that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values between two samples are correlated for low biased samples, as shown
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter_prerecon"

\end_inset

, we investigate how biases and scatter are reduced by computing the differences
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values, which will tell us the additional biases and scatter induced by
 galaxy bias.
 To test this, we take the sample with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 as a reference (denoted its 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ref}$
\end_inset

) and measure the differences in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values with the other samples.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:diffalpha_prerecon"

\end_inset

 shows the differences in shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}-\alpha_{ref}$
\end_inset

 for various HOD models corresponding to different biases.
 As expected from Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter_prerecon"

\end_inset

, the scatter is reduced from xx% to xx% for the samples with 
\begin_inset Formula $b<xxx$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, for high biases samples, the biases are reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3\%$
\end_inset

 while the scatters are almost the same.
 [what can I say more?]
\end_layout

