\begin_layout Subsection
Affects of Biased Tracers in Real-Space after Reconstruction 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:real-postrecon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the previous section, we investigate the effect of galaxy bias
 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measurements for the samples with reconstruction using the method described
 in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:fit_isotropic"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alpha_postrecon"

\end_inset

 shows the measured shifts in the BAO scale as a function of galaxy bias,
 while the right panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alpha_postrecon"

\end_inset

 shows the differences in shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}-\alpha_{ref}$
\end_inset

.
 For most of samples except the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}}M_{{\rm cut}}=13.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $13.9$
\end_inset

, the reconstruction method removes the shift and reduces the scatter on
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measurements.
 Here, we use the samples generated from the regular HOD method and the
 high biased objects tend to have large sample variances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
